@NODE Autodocs "AutoDocs"


  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_MemFree()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -30 -($1E)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       memfree,type = f_MemFree(void)
                 D0.uL    D1.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Returns the largest block of free memory in your Amiga.
                 Register D1 will contain the memorytype, in case of
                 FastRAM a NULL, else a non-NULL meaning ChipRAM.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         none

  @{b}Result@{ub}         memfree - Largest free memoryblock available
                 type    - 0=FastRAM, 1=ChipRAM

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0, d1, a1, a6

  @{b}Note@{ub}           none










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_LibBases()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -36 (-$24)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       bases = f_LibBases(void)
                 A0.Ptr

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Returns a pointer to 9 frequently used Libraries:
                  Dos- Intuition- Graphics- Gadtools- Icon- Diskfont-
                  ASL- Reqtools- Workbench-base        (respectively)

                 And do NOT deallocate the pointed area and/or libraries!

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         none

  @{b}Result@{ub}         bases - Pointer to the first longword of 9

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       a0

  @{b}Note@{ub}           So you must do this 9 times: <MOVE.L (A0)+,yourdest>











  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_ListChunks()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -42 (-$2A)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result,chunklist = f_ListChunks(filename)
                 D0.uL  D1.Ptr                   D1.Ptr

  @{b}Description@{ub}    This will build a list of all chunks out of an IFF.
                 And return the listpointer in D1, you'll have to FreeVec() it;

                 Offset  0 : Len.4 : TypeOf IFF (eg.ILBM)
                 Offset  4 : Len.4 : ChunkHeader (eg.BMHD)
                 Offset  8 : Len.4 : ChunkOffset in file
                 Offset 12 : Len.4 ...Next ChunkHeader & Offsets...
                 Offset xx : Len.4 : NULL, meaning the end

                 The function will return a result-code in D0 like:
                 SUCCESFUL       0
                 ERR_OPENINGFILE 1
                 ERR_NOMEM       2
                 ERR_READ        3
                 ERR_NOTIFF      4

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         filename  - pointer to the filename
                 
  @{b}Result@{ub}         result    - a code (see above)
                 chunklist - pointer to the list of chunks

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0, d1, d2, d3, a0, a1

  @{b}Note@{ub}           - If the IFF-file is corrupt it will return a NULL.
                 - ChunkOffset= Beginning of the Chunk including Header&Size.
                 - There is only ONE "FORM" allowed.










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_FindChunk()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -48 -($30)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_FindChunk( chunklist, chunkid )
                 D0.uL                 a0.Ptr     D0.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Find a particular ChunkHeader in your specified chunklist.
                 When found, then D0 contains the "ChunkOffset", or -1.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         chunklist - pointer to the ChunkList
                 chunkid   - an IFF-compatible ID

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result    - a ChunkOffset, or -1 when it failed

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0, d1, a0

  @{b}Note@{ub}           none










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_rtFileReq()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -54 -($36)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_rtFileReq( pref-struc )
                 D0.uL                 a0.Ptr

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Gives a filerequester according to your preferences:

                 PreferenceStructure:
                 0  4  f_RTWindow      = A WindowPtr, or null (WB)
                 4  4  f_RTMatchPat    = A MatchPatternStringPtr, or null
                 8  1  f_RTWaitPointer = Set, or null
                 9  1  f_RTMultiSelect = Set, or null for SingleFileSelection

                 Then if D0 returns non-Null, d0 will contain a ptr to a:

                 MultiSelection:
                 0  4  Pointer         : Pointer to the stringpointers
                 4  x  DirString       : The particular Directory ending with NULL
                 x  4  StringPtr 1     : Pointer to the first filename  (NULL-ended)
                 x  4  StringPtr 2     : Pointer to the second filename (NULL-en....
                 x  4  Stri..... x     : Pointer to the ...... filename (NU.....
                 x  4  NULL            : No more strings

                 or if you ordered a SingleFile-requester then d0 points to:

                 SingleSelection:
                 0  x  String          : The Path+Filename String (NULL-terminated)

                 YOU MUST FreeVec() these pointers yourself. (After usage)

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         pref-struc - pointer to a preference-structure

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result     - pointer to either a MultiSelection or FileSelection,
                              or a null when the user cancelled.

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       D0-D7/A0-A6

  @{b}Note@{ub}           ToDo: DirSelection










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_UpdatePort()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -60 (-$3C)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       waitmask, userport = f_UpdatePort(window)
                 D0.uL     A0.Ptr                  A0.Ptr

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Creates a waitmask for Wait() outof the window in A0.
                 And it returns the userport in A0 (where the intuimessages arrive).

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         window - a windowpointer

  @{b}Result@{ub}         waitmask - only including the SigBit from you window
                 userport - and the messageport for IDCMP

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0,d1,a0

  @{b}Note@{ub}           This function is very useful when you often close and
                 open (eg.) an 'option'-window; each time, the waitmask
                 and the userport must be updated then.
                 ( You can set, for instance, bit number 12 in the waitmask
                   meaning that the Wait() will be interrupted when the
                   user pressed Ctrl-C. Check "dos.i" for more Ctrls. )










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_HiresStd()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -66 (-$42)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_HiresStd(scr_width,scr_height)
                 D0.uL               D0.uL     D1.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Tests your screendimensions if it's qualified to contain
                 'hires-laced' graphics ie. that the buttons may be double-height.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         scr_width  - width of your screen
                 scr_height - height of your screen

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result - non-NULL for success, otherwise NULL

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0,d1,d2,d3,d4

  @{b}Note@{ub}           










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_BR1UnpackA()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -72 (-$48)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_BR1UnpackA(source,destination,unpackmax)
                 D0.uL                 A0.Ptr A1.Ptr      D0.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Unpacks ByteRun1-Encoded data pointed by A0 to the destination
                 pointed in A1. D0 contains a the maximum unpacksize so
                 that corrupted data won't exceed this limit.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         source    - ptr to ByteRun1-Encoded data (BODY-stuff)
                 destination - ptr to your allocated piece of memory
                 unpackmax   - maximum for unpacking

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result - NULL if succesful, else corrupted

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0,d1,d2,d3,a0,a1

  @{b}Note@{ub}           










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_BR1UnpackB()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -78 (-$4E)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_BR1UnpackA(source,destination,packedsize)
                 D0.uL                 A0.Ptr A1.Ptr      D0.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Unpacks ByteRun1-Encoded data pointed by A0 to the destination
                 pointed in A1. D0 contains the amount of packed size; the size
                 the BODY-chunk

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         source    - ptr to ByteRun1-Encoded data (BODY-stuff)
                 destination - ptr to your allocated piece of memory
                 packedsize  - size of the ByteRun1-Encoded stuff

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result - NULL if succesful, else corrupted

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0,d1,a0,a1,a2,a3

  @{b}Note@{ub}           










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_I2P()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -84 (-$54)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       f_I2P(src,   planeptrs,wpr,  bpr,  planes, height)
                       A0.Ptr A1.Ptr    D0.uL D1.uL D2.uL   D3.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Transfer interleaved data to a planar-based place. Most
                 IFF-ILBMs are interleaved, so when you f_BR1UnpackX them, they
                 must be planar if you want to have the picture be shown on Amiga.
                 (But it's possible to have an interleaved screen, if there's
                  enough contigues ChipRAM, but mostly.. planar is preferred)

                 So that's why you must supply a pointer to a list of pointers
                 pointing to all single planes. Be sure that their sizes are
                 large enough (or just the same) eg. 320x256/8

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         source    - ptr to the source, eg. the unpacked BODY
                 planeptrs - ptr to a list containing pointers to YOUR
                             allocated memory locations.
                 wpr       - words-per-row eg. 320 pixels = 20 words (word-aligned!)
                             Calculate it like this: (width+15)/16
                 bpr       - Get this from BytesPerRow(BitMap) if your destination
                             are bitplanes (eg. VGA-modes are sophisticated aligned).
                             Otherwise, in case of eg.allocated memory, it's (wpr*2).
                 height    - height/number of rows
                 planes    - = depth (if there's a mask, there's an EXTRA bitplane)

  @{b}Result@{ub}         none, it always works or you supplied wrong parameters..

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       assume ALL

  @{b}Note@{ub}           










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_P2I()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -90 (-$5A)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       result = f_P2I(planeptrs,dest   wpr,  height,planes)
                 D0.uL          A0.Ptr    A1.Ptr D0.uL D1.uL  D2.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Transfer planar data to an interleaved place. Most
                 IFF-ILBMs are interleaved, so when you f_BR1Pack them, they
                 must be interleaved if you want to have the picture saved.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         planeptrs - ptr to a list containing pointers to your
                             memory locations containing each plane
                 dest      - ptr to the destination (width*height/8*bitplanes)
                 wpr       - words-per-row eg. 320 pixels = 20 words (word-aligned!)
                             Calculate it like this: (width+15)/16
                 height    - height or number of rows
                 planes    - the number of pointers

  @{b}Result@{ub}         result - NULL if succesful, else corrupted data

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       d0,d1,d2,d3,d4,d5,d6,a0,a1,a2,a3

  @{b}Note@{ub}           










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_I2ABGR()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -96 (-$60)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       f_I2ABGR(source,destination,width,height,planes,bpr,  lineskipper,[CMAP])
                          A0.Pt  A1.Ptr      D0.uL D1.uL  D2.uL  D3.uL D4.uL       [A2.Ptr]

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Convert interleaved data to three red/green/blue guns.
                 A pixel is stored in a longword with the format: Alpha-Blue-Green-Red.
                 (ie. The precise bits represent their plane-activity from 0 to 23)
                 So that's the reason why it's not A-R-G-B.

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         source      - pointer to the interleaved (picture)data
                 destination - ptr to the destination (width*height*4)
                 width       - width in pixels
                 height      - height in pixels
                 planes      - number of planes to convert
                 bpr         - width in bytes (word-aligned!) ( (w+15)/16 *2 )
                 lineskipper - bytes, to skip each scanline (eg. 320/8 * 8 (8planes))
                 CMAP        - pointer to an area with sizeof #colors*4. Load your
                               chunk CMAP at the start of this area.
                               Remember that this area will be shapeshifted,
                               and btw. that you only have to supply this pointer
                               if the picture has 8 or less bitplanes + a CMAP.
                 
  @{b}Result@{ub}         If YOU give sane parameters, it all will be allright

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       ALL

  @{b}Note@{ub}           It's possible to get only for instance the blue gun.
                 Just add eg. 320/8*16 to A0 and set planes to 8.
                                  (!In case of a 24-bit picture!)










  @{b}Name@{ub}           f_SaveRGB8()

  @{b}Lib.Offset@{ub}     -102 (-$66)

  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}       f_SaveRGB8(source,width,height,filename,displayid)
                            A0.Ptr D0.uL D1.u   D2.uL    D3.uL

  @{b}Description@{ub}    Save your ABGR-buffer to disk in IFF-RGB8 format. (24bit)

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}         source    - pointer to an ABGR
                 width     - in pixels
                 height    - in pixels
                 filename  - ptr to a string
                 displayid - a displayid for the CAMG-chunk

  @{b}Result@{ub}         always succesful

  @{b}Reg.Used@{ub}       assume all

  @{b}Note@{ub}           This format is the fastest of all!








